Question: What is the way to use stringtokenizer: :I have used the code to extract each digit of the string,my motive is to store it in an integer array,but i am unable to extract all the digits of the stringimport java.util.StringTokenizer;   class jdsh    {        public static void main()        {int i,j;            String a="1 2 3 4";            StringTokenizer aa= new StringTokenizer(a);            for(i=0;i<=aa.countTokens();i++)            System.out.println(aa.nextToken());        }    }
Please using this api: StringTokenizer.nextToken.
Answer: $CODE
StringTokenizer aa= new StringTokenizer(a);
int[] intArray = new int[aa.countTokens()];
for(int i=0; i<intArray.length; i++) {
    intArray[i] = Integer.parseInt(aa.nextToken());
}

Explanation: In the code, we first create a StringTokenizer object 'aa' with the string "1 2 3 4". We then create an integer array 'intArray' with the same number of elements as the tokens in the string. We then use a for loop to iterate over the array. In each iteration, we use the nextToken method of StringTokenizer to get the next token from the string, and then use the Integer.parseInt method to convert the token to an integer. We store this integer in the corresponding element of the array.

